text:
We took a local tip for the best pizza in Chicago.   It's a dive vibe with a very regimented process.   The garlic bread was good and the dipping sauce was a nice touch.

Pizza came fairly quickly.  A standard deep dish with sausage, onion and pepper.  Good crust, good flavor for sauce and toppings were perfect.

Service was quick and attentive.  A great experience.

The pizza here was amazing! I have never had deep dish pizza and I am glad I made it my first experience. It was loaded with toppings and very filling!
The service was great as well and everyone was so kind.
I will definitely make this a regular stop when I'm in Chicago.

this place is definitely worth the hype. my bf and i came in around 5 pm. it was busy!!! make a reservation ahead if you are planning on going during the weekend. we got a large pepperoni+sausage, it was perfect! love the atmosphere, the staffs are attentive and kind.

This is Chicago's best deep dish. The crust might be burnt but everything else is just right. The dough at the bottom maintains it's moisture so it's not hard and crunchy. Good variety of toppings to choose from. Great customer service. They have qr codes so you can order online at your table without waiting for service if you're really introverted. There's also a second floor for additional seating and restrooms.

I‚Äôll start by acknowledging that I‚Äôm no expert on Chicago-style pizza‚ÄîI can only share my experience based on what I tasted.

With that said, this pizza place came highly recommended by several people as a must-try for authentic Chicago-style pizza.

I made the journey from downtown, waited three hours (passing the time by catching a movie across the street), and finally sat down to order. I went with a large pizza (though I initially wanted a medium, but no big deal), some wings (skip), and a Caesar salad (also skip). Then, the much-anticipated pizza arrived.

Yes, the pepperoni was nicely toasted, and yes, the crust was crisp and crunchy. But for me, it didn‚Äôt hit the flavor notes I was hoping for. It didn‚Äôt leave me thinking, ‚ÄúWow, I can‚Äôt wait to come back!‚Äù

Maybe my expectations were too high, or perhaps I just don‚Äôt know what I‚Äôm talking about when it comes to Chicago pizza.

But for me, Pequod‚Äôs didn‚Äôt live up to the hype.

Apologies, Chicagoans. üòî

Our server was Samantha. She was so attentive and did a great job explaining how to order to our group of five.

The pizza is better than giordano's pizza. The dough on the pizza is soft and so yummy. The sauce isn‚Äôt sweet either.

The house made sausage is fantastic!

It was my first visit. The other three family members had visited earlier. The service was good  The food was decent. My family members commented it wasn‚Äôt as good as earlier. The pizza crust was burnt, but that could be due to my requesting the pizza to be well done. However, Pequod‚Äôs needs to do some serious pest control. I caught, using a napkin, a roach climbing the wall next to our table. And my daughter has a dead one on the table next to her plate. The staff comped us a pizza. Thanks. But please do pest control immediately. I have come away with mixed feelings. Considering the hoops I had to go through to get a table, it‚Äôs not worth it. But, will I go back and give them a second chance? Yes, but only after post control.

Went here when my family was in town so that they could get some deep dish. We all got personal pan pizzas - mine was cheese. They let you personalize them with your toppings, which was great since everyone at the table was all over the place with topping desires. We also got an order of fries (crispy, delicious) and the house salad (super basic but surprisingly good). I got an Arnold Palmer to drink. We made a reservation online ahead of time because we heard it gets busy and the line gets long. They seated us right away upstairs. We ordered with the QR code on our table and also the server who was bopping by regularly enough. They had some sports games on the TV and it was quite loud upstairs with people chatting and some music playing - this is just something to note if you‚Äôre looking for a place super quiet and intimate! The prices were totally reasonable and the quality of the pizza was good. The sauce was a little more herby than other deep dish recipes in the city. I‚Äôm not a huge fan of deep dish so will probably try the thin crust next time. Will be back when the time is right.

Did not had a good experience. We made a reservation and our server was so confused and felt like they are not trained. First of all she did not gave us the table we have to find ourself. Secondly the food we ordered went to wrong table and finally wen it came we were not happy with the taste. Salad had very less dressing. Pizza was okay not that great.  Thin crust was good and the fries.

Although there was a bit of confusion on where to seat my group when I came in on time for my reservation, the staff was very friendly and made our overall experience a good one! The place was very crowded and at times it felt a bit tight and crammed, however we were seated right by the door; other seating areas likely offer a better experience. We ordered a regular deep dish and thin crust cheese pizza; both were good and tasted very fresh! Nonetheless, I‚Äôve had better of both types of pizza at other locations. Despite this, I still think the pizza is a solid choice for anyone looking to try it!

Make a reservation, no matter what time you plan to come. Be patient.... Pizza takes at least an hour.    Always get extra cheese.   It's so worth the wait, parking headache, and cost.   5 stars all day

First time trying Chicago Style pizza, and I enjoyed the experience. I asked a friend from Chicago where should I go and this was the top place. I have an individual deep dish with all veggies and everything was super fresh! The pizza was more than I could ever eat! Although I am not a fan of saucy pizza, the freshness of this pizza was a big plus! If you like think crust pizza with a lot of sauce, this is your spot! I will just stick to what I like, thin crust! Thanks for the perfect intro to Chicago style pizza!

Was told this is the spot for Chicago deep dish pizza by my friend who has lived there for a long time. Was also told getting a table is difficult and both are true. Make a reservation well before. I made ours a week out and the only time we could get in was 5pm. The restaurant is really cute and casual, staff is super friendly and the pizza did not disappoint! I got cheese with basil and fresh garlic. My friend got sausage and pepperoni and we both really enjoyed them. I also got the house salad, she got the Caesar, really good size for a starter salad. Fresh and yummy, forgot to take a pic of them tho. ü§¶üèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è Definitely recommend and will be back for sure.

Yum, yes please! First time at this pizza joint Pequod‚Äôs and it was amazing!! At first sight, the pizza comes in a giant pan and appears burnt around the edges, however, once you dig in, it certainly does not taste burnt! It‚Äôs a butter dough crust that is simply delicious! This pizza is a work of art! Highly recommend ordering extra sauce and extra cheese! Worth the wait! Good drinks and good food! Sean the GM was splendid to work with! Will definitely return!!

In my opinion, Pequod's is the second best non-NY style pizza in the USA, just behind Bocce Club in Buffalo, NY. Pequod's is my go-to whenever I'm in the Windy City. Just can't be beat. Ice cold draft beer and pizza. Also, I wanna add that the meatballs are some of the best meatballs I've ever eaten.

I‚Äôve heard that Pequad‚Äôs was the best deep dish in Chicago, so I took a detour on a trip I was on recently to try it out. I was there for lunch on the Monday after Christmas, so take that into account for level of busyness and service.
I arrived around 11:30, and was able to sit down immediately at the bar. I was there alone, so a group might take longer to sit. I did notice that it got significantly more busy as it got closer to noon, and when I left there was a line.
Walking in, the hostess and GM were very friendly and sat me right away after asking if I was ok sitting at the bar. The bartender was very friendly, and took my order rather than making me go through the online ordering system they have in place. She was also very responsive to any requests for drink refills, check, etc.
The food was good, but I was expecting a little better for it being considered the best in Chicago. I had a pan pizza. The edges were crispy, sort of like a Jets pizza, if you are familiar with Detroit Pan Pizza. The sauce and cheese were about what I expect from a handmade pizza place. I did notice that the cheese texture seemed to be better on the second slice, so maybe let the pizza rest a little when they bring it to your table.
Two slices were more than enough for me on my 10‚Äù pan pizza, figure that it is about the same amount of food as three or even four slices of a large pizza from elsewhere. I took the rest home, and it was very good the second, third, and fourth time I ate it.
Parking was a little difficult, but I was able to find a spot in the residential neighborhood behind the restaurant and walked a bit. I don‚Äôt know if was supposed to pay or not, but I didn‚Äôt see any signs, meters, or painted curbs to suggest that I was not supposed to park there.
I don‚Äôt know if I would go terribly far out of my way to visit, but for me it was only about 30 minutes more of driving, so I am glad I had the experience.

Great affordable deep dish pizza! Our group of 5 had a reservation at 7pm on a Wednesday. We ordered mozzarella sticks, jalapeno poppers, half caesar salad, cheesy garlic bread, and a 14'' pie with mushrooms and Italian sausage along with some drinks. It was plenty of food, and we ended up having some deep dish leftover. You order via QR code, so you're really only seeing the wait staff when they drop off your food/drinks. Deep dish was delicious and very filling though I'm personally still a bigger fan of thin crust pizza. Everyone was also big fans of the mozzarella sticks and jalapeno poppers as well.

TL;DR - Long wait but decent pizza!

Food:
- Deep dish pizza: The pizza has a decent sauce though I find it a bit under-seasoned. Either way, I think it's pretty good. The only criticism I have is that more oil should be used in the pan for a crispier bottom of the crust. The dough was fully cooked but it lacked the expected crispiness--though this does not mean that it's a consistent issue. It could just have been due to them being very busy because of the race.

I liked this place. Just keep in mind that it takes about 45 mins for a deep dish to be cooked. So, while you'll wait for a while for the food, that's just the nature of a deep dish. Don't be rude to the staff because of this.

‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê

Took our clients to Pequod‚Äôs Pizza while in Chicago for an industry convention, and it did not disappoint! üçïüî• If you‚Äôre looking for an authentic taste of Chicago deep dish, this is the spot. The food was incredible, and the service was top-notch. üôå

The staff gave us some great recommendations while we waited for the pizza‚Äîdefinitely ask them for tips! üëç Just remember to be patient, because the pizza is absolutely worth the wait. üçΩÔ∏è

I highly recommend making a reservation in advance, especially since the space is cozy but has lots of hidden seating (check out upstairs!). üèôÔ∏è Pro tip: come hungry and don‚Äôt fill up too much on appetizers while you‚Äôre waiting! üòã

Would love to return next time we‚Äôre in town!

First time ever having proper deep dish pizza. Was recommended by a store clerk, and made my way over. Definitely local spot, with close knit staff and no standard outfit for job. The pizza was heavenly and the service was quick and nice! Good selection of toppers with salt, chili flakes, S&P and parm.

Came here right when they opened and we got seated immediately. It was still a long wait for the pizzas but worth the wait. Best deep dish pizza I've had, the cheese was melty and gooey and eat slice was packed with toppings. The onion rings were a hit too.

The caramelized crust is totally worth it! It's a more pub than grill kind of spot.  3 hour wait with reserverations. But we ordered ahead (and you are not allowed to dine in if you ordered ahead we found out!) But just 2 doors down we picked up our pizza pie and actually ate it there in the pick up lobby
Fantastic sauce!

All I can say is that it is an excellent pizza.
Perhaps my favorite deep dish in the USA.  Everyone raves about the Sauce crust slightly buttered and caramelized, which is yummy. I will add their sauce is superior to others.  It is thicker, richer, and less acidic, a robust, sweet sauce made with tomato sauce, spices, and other ingredients.

First visit from out of state. Pequod‚Äôs is a true gem for deep-dish lovers. The standout feature is their amazing caramelized crust‚ÄîWe had the pepperoni and sausage classic, which was absolutely delicious. The toppings are generous, and the sauce is perfectly balanced, and a load of cheese. While reservations are recommended, we were seated without one. The atmosphere is casual, fun, and welcoming, making it a great spot for groups or families. Excellent service and a Chicago pizza experience you won‚Äôt forget. Highly recommend!

We love your pizza and are ordering from Goldbelly. Most recent experience was no so great. 3 out of 4 pizzas were phenomenal but not sure what went wrong with this cheese pizza. Dough have not risen and was very much underbaked despite‚Äôs long time in the oven. Pizza was not edible and had to be thrown out. What went wrong?

NOW THIS IS LIVING! Unbuckle your pants. Take your lactaid and wrap in for a truly Chicago Deep dish pizza!! I was pretty full from my lunch but powered through to try this Chicago staple. I got a personal pizza with black olives, sausage, meatballs, extra cheese and fresh basil. I could only eat half of pizza but every bite was just like a little party. All of the flavors and the dough come together in such a great way. Now I will say it‚Äôs messy and I would advise you eat it with a knife and fork. The service was attentive and helpful and there was lots of places to sit and I didn‚Äôt have to wait. But went pretty early on a snowy Monday. The pizza is pretty hot when it arrives so be patient and let it cool down. Also I think each pizza takes about 30 minutes to make so be patient when you go.

This is the place to try Chicago deep dish pizza. Lunch is very busy, so reservations are recommended. The personal pan size is perfect, leaving you sated but not feeling unwell after eating it. I definitely suggest getting giardiniera and meatballs as toppings. Skip the Italian beef. Don't bother paying for fresh basil, which is literally one measly leaf. You order from a QR code via Toast, but good luck trying to get a server to refill your water or bring you a to go box. Nevertheless, if you want deep dish, it's worth it.

The hype is real. The deep dish pan pizza here definitely lived up to it. Detroit style meets Chicago deep dish. The crispy caramelized cheese edges were incredible. We went for takeout but the vibe of the place itself is very dive-y which is not bad. Beware, there's typically a ~40 minute wait for this pizza so the best option is to order ahead before arriving.

Definitely a must visit if you're in Chicago!

My first time trying deep dish, and wow, what an underwhelming experience.

Food: The quality of the pizza ingredients was terrible. The meat? Chewy, like gnawing on a cardboard box. The cheese? Unevenly spread, with half the pizza mysteriously missing any at all. After this, I genuinely don‚Äôt understand the hype around deep dish‚Äîespecially from what‚Äôs supposedly the most popular place in Chicago.

Service: It‚Äôs a popular spot, so sure, I get the three-hour wait if you don‚Äôt have a reservation. As a non-local, I wasn‚Äôt aware of this. When I mentioned it to the reception staff, their snarky response was, ‚ÄúWe‚Äôve been taking online reservations for five years now.‚Äù Well, thank you, Sarcastic Nancy, for the enlightening history lesson. üòí Anyway, we ended up getting a take-out.

Had to try was everyone called the "best deep dish" in Chicago. For the record id tried giardiano's and lou malnati's previously and I have to agree with the public-- Pequod's is the best! The sauce is saucy with the texture of crush tomatoes but not tangy like some pizza sauces are. It was seasoned well. The crust was caramelized and the texture was perfect. I think what sets this deep dish apart is how well the crust holds up with the toppings. Often the deep dish experience means that the integrity of the crust is compromised by the weight of all the ingredients and the sauce but this crust was deliciously solid and hd everything together well, making it the perfect bite of deep dish deliciousness.

The service was amazing and our server was so sweet. I didn't make a reservation prior which I didnt know you had to do but they accommodates us upstairs. There is a nice selection of local beers and we had the Maple Son of Juice.

The pizzas take about 40 minutes but it's definitely worth it. We ordered a salad and wings and they were brought out prior. The salad was fresh and crisp with an amazing dressing and the wings were crispy and not overly sauced.

We opted for a personal pan pepperoni and mushroom pizza. Well aware that's it's for one person but to be honest this pizza is so filling! I have no idea how people can eat a whole pie but our server said she's seen people house a whole deep dish pizza on their own! They must be built different because after half a personal, I was full.

This is definitely a spot I recommend if your eint he a Chicago area.

Super Rad and the first deep dish pizza I've ever eaten in Chicago..

Sausage was a life changer for me give me new meaning of body flavor and a really nice licorice zest to The Taste in Aroma.

I ate the medium deep dish pizza with pepperoni and sausage. It was worth every penny it was stellar...

Honestly the best sausage I've ever had on Pizza in my lifeüòÉüî•.

Thanks to the craftsmanship that goes into this pizza establishment highly skilled individuals and great personality and character definitely something to cherish when visiting Chicago.....

Eben

I've heard so much about this place. I was so thrilled to finally check it out. We did a take out order. Honestly, I'm so glad they're open later than most typical pizza joints in the city. We ordered a deep dish with sausage, peperoni, and mushrooms. The crust was delicious, nice and crispy, but some parts were black very burnt. Ehhhh, 4/5 on the crust. The sausage was disappointing, to say the least. It was more like gigantic meatballs 2/5 for the toppings. The peperoni and mushrooms were fabulous, tho. Perfect amout of sauce. Next time, I'll get extra cheese, but it was still good. The inside looked bomb.com when we drove past. I'm definitely eating in-house next time. All in all, I definitely recommend this establishment, give em all your money. Can't wait to go back!

I had to try the infamous deep dish pizza while in Chicago, and I heard this is better quality than Giordanos. I was pleasantly surprised with how tasty it was!

My favorite pizza style is Neapolitan, so I wasn‚Äôt expecting to enjoy it as much as I did. I got the personal size and added garlic, tomatoes, basil and sausage. Every bite was like a flavor bomb, and the caramelized crust also added to that.

Overall, I‚Äôm glad I tried this style pizza but will stick with my thin crust Neapolitans!

Definitely worth the wait and the visit when you are in Chicago! The pizza was so delicious, amazing crust! It‚Äôs easy to be tempted to add lots of toppings, but we only did a few (I.e. pepperoni and basil) and it was spot on! We ordered a small pizza and it was great amount for two people, it‚Äôs very filling.

This location is a lot bigger than it seems! There is meter street parking in the area and a bathroom inside.

The pizza wait time that was quoted was about 45 minutes, but it came out in 30 minutes! I ordered some garlic bread as appetizer during the wait which helped since we were starving!

The waitress told us we can do a half-and-half order too which was nice.

The slightly burnt cheesy crust on the pizza was absolutely delicious. Definitely worth the wait! I ended up ordering two frozen sausage pizzas to-go.

I will be back for future pan pizza cravings. :)
This has to be the greatest pizza I have ever eaten, bar none! Was a destination spot on my recent trip to Chicago and was well worth the extra effort. Highly recommended!

Requires reservations!!
We arrived here without reservations on a Saturday at 11:30 and very fortunately was able to get a table! For others coming in without reservations it was an hour or more wait! So definitely call ahead before showing up.

Anyway, the service was fantastic. The pizza was definitely the best deep dish we had on our trip. The location is a bit out of way for tourist but the nearby neighborhood is cool to explore (especially with the Halloween decorations). Overall I highly recommend making reservations and coming here!

As amazing as you've heard. It's like deep dish built on the best pan crust ever. I was impressed by the size of the restaurant. We had reservations long in advance, but it didn't seem too crowded around noon during a summer Friday. The service was really nice and chill. Our waiter Alex was great! Can't wait to visit again. I'll be craving this pizza!!

Their caramelized pizza is amazing. The bread is very thick and ‚Äúbready‚Äù lol but the sauce, cheese , and we got pepperoni, was so good. Their pizza is really the star of the show. Their cheesy garlic bread is the other thing we got and it was good, but nothing out of this world. Their pizza gets very burnt but that‚Äôs their style and it‚Äôs soooo good. I would recommend trying this place out. I love that they are open late too which helps so much. Their deep dish pizza takes about 40 minutes so it was a bit of a wait if you are in a hurry, but it is worth it.

One of the best chicago style pizza.
Super delicious, fresh ingredients not so oily, it‚Äôs massive so highly recommended to eat it at least in group of 2-3c make sure as well to make reservations can be quite busy.

The staff at this restaurant is very friendly and helpful.   The pizza is amazing!  The way to order food is a hassle, you can't just tell the waiter your order.  It has to go through an app which isn't great and doesn't make for a great atmosphere.

Very unique taste.  I‚Äôve lived in and around Chicago my whole life and this pizza is different.  Definitely worth a trip to check it out.  Please note the first picture is a personal pizza and the second picture is a small pizza. I couldn‚Äôt finish the personal but we did get cheesy garlic bread as well, so that might be the reason.

First time here a friend recommended it and it did not disappoint my wife and ai tried the 7inch Chicago pizza and it was good. We also had a 10inch tavern style pizza and we were split my wife loved the Chicago style pizza and I loved the tavern style my advice try both and enjoy

We enjoyed our deep dish pizza. Just what we expected. The staff were great and provided good recommendations. We weren't a fan of waiting 45 mins gor pizza, but other than that, everything else was great.

Go big or go home, Pequod‚Äôs delivers. Their not-so-deep dish pan pizza is excellent with the carmelized cheese around the outside of the crust. It‚Äôs deep dish without being deep. Bring and appetite and enjoy.

I was really excited to try my first ever chicago deep dish at Pequods's as I love a good caramelized crust, but ultimately, it was just okay. My friend and I shared a small pepperoni pizza, with half garlic and basil and the other half pepper and onions. The marinara sauce was amazing and the toppings were plentiful but the actual pizza crust did not taste like anything except for the caramelized edge, which is sad given that the crust makes up so much of the pizza and the bottom pizza crust (beneath the soft thick crust) tasted and had the consistency of plain crispy toast. Overall, Pequod's has the warm feel of a mom and pop shop, the service was great and I am glad they were able to squeeze us in at the bar on a saturday night, but I‚Äôm not in a hurry to go back.
Personally I am not a fan of deep dish pizza but was glad to try this. The pizza was fully loaded with ingredients and the crust had a nice crunch. Best to reserve a table ahead as it was busy.

Had a 1:30 reservation and got there early and they sat me right away. Since I was a 1 person reservation, they sit you at the bar which I‚Äôm not a fan of as I don‚Äôt drink and I‚Äôm short but the next available table was 10pm, so I took a bar seat. I was not disappointed at all.

Pizza was great and Jeff, server/bartender amazing! Helped me out by charging my phone as well as kept my glass filled with water for the duration of my dining.

Very Busy place. Son Made reservations 2weeks in advance, our table was available! Sadly, we had to go up narrow set of lighted steps this was hard for my handicap spouse. The host saw he was handicap and there were tables on main floor that. He could have given us but no took is upstairs! Sadly host doesn't think outside the box! Deep dish Pizza was delicious it takes approximately 45 minutes to make one large. EXTRA TOPPINGS ARE EXPENSIVE be sure to ASK the charge B4 as we added 3 extra almost as much as Pizza itself!!!

This is my first time actually dine in after living in Chicago for 4 years. It is always good to make an appointment ahead of time otherwise it is hard to sit inside on the day. We ordered sausage pan pizza, we love the crust but at the same time feel the bread is probably too thick that we don‚Äôt feel like sauce and cheese is enough. But the vibe there feels local and less like a chain restaurant.

Hands down the best pizza I have had in the city! The $7.95 lunch special is seriously a good deal and the perfect amount of food. My husband tried the thin crust with pepperoni and giardiniera and it was amazing! The giardiniera had the perfect amount of heat to it and worked well with the cheese. If you like to dip your pizza in sauce - the creamy garlic dressing was perfect. Max was our server and super friendly, hospitable, and attentive! Can‚Äôt wait to come back next time we are in the city.

This place is among the most popular spots for Chicago pizza in town. I can only confirm to go there to try the Chicago pizza. It was  so delicious. Of note, place is super popular so I would suggest to reserve  your table in advance and take into account with your booking time reservation that probably you will have to wait an additional 30 mins to get the table. That was our experience on a Monday evening.
My favorite deep dish spot in Chicago, with a delicious caramelized crust. They do tavern style pizzas here as well. Overall vibe is very casual with a good selection of beers as well.

Chicago visitors and locals alike know the allure of deep dish pizza and the rivalries between the local pizzerias. Pequod's sits in the thick of the conversation. For me, Pequod's is good ‚Äì but not great ‚Äì among all the best-known options out there today. The cheese pulls were great. The charred crust was unique and added texture. But the sauce is what held this pizza back. The strongest flavor was tomato paste, and it was a bit dry relative to the rest of the pie. It could've used a bit more flavor as well ‚Äì maybe a fat or an acid, not a spice. Don't let my critique steer you away, though. Pequod's is still good pizza and worth the visit! At the very least they're a great local option if you're open to trying a new spot for deep dish

I was excited to try their pan pizza while I was in town after a recommendation from a friend and seeing the pictures of the top of the pizza. The sauce, pepperonis, and crusty edge were delicious, but it was way too much bread for me. I'm not sure if I ordered the wrong pizza or if they add more dough for delivery orders.

I got a Personal Pan pizza with meatballs and giardiniera for dine-in.
The pizza did as promised, take a while to make, and arrived well crisped.
Overall though, I was a bit disappointed by the crumbliness of the result - the pizza was still impossible to eat without cutting it into pieces because the middle sogged so much.
The meatball was also sliced very thin so behaved much more like slices of pepperoni, and wasn‚Äôt very strongly spiced at all.
Overall, I was quite disappointed, and I am not sure what I could change about my order that would improve the results. I love the concept of their pizzas, but the execution just didn‚Äôt fulfil that promise for me.

This place is pretty neat, much bigger inside than it appeared.  We sat on the second floor which was fine, I was a bit surprised that Friday at 11:40 I was asked if we had a reservation.   When we left and there was a line out the door I understood why.  The pan pizza was OK, reminded me of Pizza Hut breadsticks covered in sauce and cheese.  (Judge me however you want, I like Pizza Hut breadsticks)  Our small pizza took about 40 mins to come out, which our server told us about ahead of time.  If Chicago pizza is your thing then stop here and give it a shot.

Quite simply the best ever pizza I‚Äôve eaten in my life. I don‚Äôt know what else I can say. The deep pan is mind blowing, order down a size from what you think, it‚Äôs filling and everyone is taking home half their pizza in a doggy bag!

This Pizza is by far the best ever! We ordered a deep dish with pepperoni and meatballs....yummazing! The location is a cozy neighborhood spot with a mix of locals and tourists. It was a fun vibe. Full no-frills bar. You order via the toast app but the servers still come by often to check in, so that was great! Just go, it will be well worth it!

First time having deep dish and I was recommend this place by several people. I was told it‚Äôs the best deep dish in Chicago and man oh man I believe it! I would say it‚Äôs the best pizza I‚Äôve ever had hands down. The pizza is the perfect amount of everything! Sauce was so great, cheese was great, literally have nothing bad to say. Also got the wings which were also tasty. Highly recommend this place even if it‚Äôs an hour drive from you.

My wife and I were so excited to eat this pizza!  A friend  who , between the 2 of us have eaten at enough restaurants that together could have paid off a mortgage on a  small home, highly recommend Pequod's Pizza.

Well with my first bite the excitement vanished! What a disappointment!
First I noticed that the sauce lacked flavor .
I commented to my wife that" this sauce is flat, it needs spices."

I have been reading a lot if reviews  about the "caramelized crust" If you are a fan of burnt cheese, then by all means give the place rave reviews. I would not call this cheese caramelized. The burnt cheese is bitter and changes the flavor of the pizza making it taste, well? Burnt! I had to remove the burnt edges to eat the pizza.
The dough to cheese ratio was good and the taste was average at best.
We ordered a sausage and mushroom deep dish. Although there was enough sausage and mushrooms the size of the sausage was too large to enjoy without having to be cut into smaller pieces.  Personally I think that sausage pieces  should be  the diameter of a  penny but no larger than a nickel.  These chunks were the size of fork prongs and could have easily been divided into 4 or 5 bite sized pieces.
The flavor of the sausage was okay, but certainly not the best I've tasted.
I can't believe that people rate this the best pan pizza in Chicago. This is not the best that Chicago has to offer. There are many deep dish pizza restaurants in Chicago that offer a better product. Try as many as you can.
Now that I have tried it I won‚Äôt be returning. I prefer Labriola deep dish.
Buon appetito
Went after catching a concert. There is a wait unless you take the bar..pretty much order through the QR code....pizza was amazing. Carmelized crust, plenty of toppings and not too doughy.
An awesome pizza place. One of the best pizza restaurants in town. The service was good. The beer was great. The bathrooms were nasty.

Chicago Deep Dish Pizza, commonly called Chicago Pizza for short, is a specialty food that cannot be missed when talking about Chicago. It is also famous as the eternal rival of New York pizza, which is closer to Italian style.

If I were to be honest, I personally prefer New York pizza, but I've never actually tasted proper Chicago pizza before. This is the pizza restaurant that I visited to experience the authentic taste since I was in the hometown.

The location is far from downtown, so it has a local flavor, and most importantly, it is not a franchise. If you have good accessibility and don't mind a franchise, you can go to Giordanos.

While New York pizza places usually have an Italian feel, this place really reminds you of a shabby pub when you open the door. Even though it doesn't suit you, reservations are accepted and almost always recommended.

I made a reservation in advance in Korea and was immediately guided to the second floor, and there was no single customer in sight except me. I was a little cringe-worthy because I was next to the big American brother and sisters, but I sat firmly.

You don't have to worry about whether you can eat an entire deep dish by yourself because the minimum size is 1 serving. I ordered a deep dish with added toppings and waited while drinking a glass of cold ale.

They said it would take about 40 minutes for the deep dish to come out, but it actually took less than that. I thought it was a small portion since it was for one person, but I was quite taken aback when I saw the size of the deep dish on the plate.

Three toppings were added: pepperoni, Italian beef, and green pepper. Although it was a bit excessive, it was not a bad choice. If you don't add any toppings, the only ingredient is cheese.

First of all, the taste was intuitive and simple, and as I heard, it was very heavy. Even leaving all the toppings aside, the amount of mozzarella cheese was almost pouring, so it filled my mouth.

This made me think that the dough would have to be thick, so it didn't feel too burdensome. It maintained a solid shape and supported the weight well, and the edges added crispness.

The pepperoni and Italian beef were, as expected, salty and fatty, but when they met the cheese and fell limply in the mouth, the harmony was truly amazing. Even though they were both obviously heavy, they seemed to be suppressing each other.

The bell peppers were roasted together in the oven as a last resort for balance, but they still had a slightly crunchy texture, making them a delicacy. It didn't stand out because I drank beer, but it did give me a sense of refreshment.

Salt, pepper and a few spices are placed on the table so you can add them if necessary. At the last minute, I found myself choking on some red pepper seeds and putting them in my mouth even though I couldn't get any more.

P.S. It doesn't seem that bad even without toppings.
